== Testing for biological molecules
#point[
Describe and carry out the Benedict’s test for reducing
sugars, the iodine test for starch, the emulsion test for lipids
and the biuret test for proteins
]
#centrebold[Reducing sugar test]\
Reducing sugars can be tested for by making them into a solution, adding Benedict's solution,
and allowing it to be heated for some time and observing colour change.
- Green colour indicates low concentration of reducing sugar present.
- Orange to red colours indicate higher concentrations of reducing sugars present, proportional
  to intensity of colour seen.

#centrebold[Iodine test]\
Adding aqueous iodine onto any substance and observing a colour change from red-brown to blue-black
indicates presence of starch.

#centrebold[Emulsion test]\
After dissolving a sample in ethanol, and mixing in water, a cloudy white emulsion should form in
presence of lipids.

#centrebold[Biuret test]\
Addition of biuret solution into sample and observing colour change from blue to purple (mauve)
indicates presence of protein.

#point[
Describe and carry out a semi-quantitative Benedict’s test
on a reducing sugar solution by standardising the test and
using the results (time to first colour change or comparison to
colour standards) to estimate the concentration
]
For higher reducing sugar concentrations, colour change takes shorter period of time. However,
semi-quantitive colour change follows
- Green colour indicates low concentration of reducing sugar present.
- Orange to red colours indicate higher concentrations of reducing sugars present, proportional
  to intensity of colour seen.

#point[
Describe and carry out a test to identify the presence of
non-reducing sugars, using acid hydrolysis and Benedict’s
solution
]
Addition of acids into a sample and then performing Benedict's test indicates presence of a
non-reducing sugar. The non-reducing sugar is hydrolysed by the acid, forming reducing sugars.

