#point[
Define the terms monomer, polymer, macromolecule,
monosaccharide, disaccharide and polysaccharide
]
A _monomer_ is a relatively simple molecule which is used as a basic building block for the
synthesis of a polymer -- many monomers join together by covalent bonds to form the polymer.

A _polymer_ is a giant molecule made from many similar repeating subunits covalently bonded
together in a chain.
#v(0.5em)
A _monosaccharide_ is a molecule consisting of a single sugar unit and with the general formula
#ch("(CH2O)_n"). Glucose, fructose and galactose are monosaccharides with six carbons (hexose),
whereas ribose and deoxyribose are monosaccharides with five carbons (pentose).

A _disaccharide_ is a sugar molecule consisting of two monosaccharides joined together by a
glycosidic bond. A _polysaccharide_ is a polymer whose subunits are monosaccharides joined
together by glycosidic bonds.

#point[
State the role of covalent bonds in joining smaller molecules
together to form polymers
]
The formation of polymers from monomers occurs due to formation of covalent bonds between the
monomers.

#point[
State that glucose, fructose and maltose are reducing sugars
and that sucrose is a non-reducing sugar
]
Note that, maltose (glucose + glucose) and sucrose (glucose + fructose) are disaccharides.

#point[
Describe the formation of a glycosidic bond by condensation,
with reference to disaccharides, including sucrose, and
polysaccharides
]
Glycosidic bonds form by _condensation reactions_, where two hydroxyl groups line up alongside
each other and one combines with a hydrogen atom from the other to form a water molecule. This
results in a link of #ch("--C--O--C--") between the two saccharide molecules. Repeated condensation
gives rise to polysaccharides.

#point[
Describe the breakage of a glycosidic bond in
polysaccharides and disaccharides by hydrolysis, with
reference to the non-reducing sugar test
]
Heating disaccharide or polysaccharide solutions in presence of hydrochloric acid breaks the
glycosidic bond and gives rise to the monomers again.

#point[
Describe the molecular structure of the polysaccharides
starch (amylose and amylopectin) and glycogen and relate
their structures to their functions in living organisms
]
Living organisms store glucose in their bodies as it is the main source of energy for cells. In
plants, the storage polysaccharide is _starch_ and in animals it is _glycogen_.
#centrebold[Starch]\
Starch is a mixture of two substances: amylose and amylopectin. _Amylose_ consists of condensations
between $alpha$-glucose molecules forming 1,4 linkages. A curved chain forms which coil up into
helical structures similar to springs, making the final molecule compact. _Amylopectin_ consists
also of 1,4 linkages but the chains are shorter than in amylose and also contain 1,6 linkages which
are branches out the sides of the chain.

#centrebold[Glycogen]\
Glycogen is the storage molecule in animals, which is made of chains of 1,4 linked $alpha$-glucose
with 1,6 linkages making branch points. The molecules clump together to form granules, visible in
liver and muscle cells.

