#point[
Describe the molecular structure of the polysaccharide
cellulose and outline how the arrangement of cellulose
molecules contributes to the function of plant cell walls
]
_Cellulose_ is a polysaccharide made from $beta$-glucose subunits, which is used as a strengthening
material in plant walls. The linkages between subsequence subunits are 1,4, however the structure
of the $beta$-glucose monomer makes it such that subsequent subunits are rotated $180degree$.

#point[
State that triglycerides are non-polar hydrophobic molecules
and describe the molecular structure of triglycerides with
reference to fatty acids (saturated and unsaturated), glycerol
and the formation of ester bonds
]
_Triglycerides_ are lipids that form from ester linkages between one glycerol molecule and three
fatty acid molecules. A _saturated_ fatty acid contains only singly bonded carbon atoms and an
_unsaturated_ fatty acid contains atleast one doubly bonded carbon pair.

#point[
Relate the molecular structure of triglycerides to their functions
in living organisms
]
Triglycerides are the most common form of _lipids_. They are stored just below the skin and act as
insulators. When oxidised in respiration, triglycerides can be converted to carbon dioxide and
water, so they act as a source of energy.

#point[
Describe the molecular structure of phospholipids with
reference to their hydrophilic (polar) phosphate heads and
hydrophobic (non-polar) fatty acid tails
]
Phospholipid molecules has one end soluble in water (_hydrophillic head_) as one of the fatty acids
is replaced by a phosphate group. The two remaining fatty acids are still hydrophobic and are
called the hydrophobic tail.

