#point[
Explain the meaning of the terms primary structure,
secondary structure, tertiary structure and quaternary
structure of proteins
]
Proteins consist of many amino acids joined by peptide bonds. The _primary structure_ of a protein
is the sequence of amino acids in the protein.

The _secondary structure_ of a protein molecule
is that which results from the regular coiling ($alpha$-helix) and folding of the chain of amino
acids ($beta$-pleated sheets). which arises due to hidrogen bonding between the oxygen of the
#ch("C==O") group and the hydrogen of the #ch("N--H") group of the amino acid four places ahead.
If the hydrogen bonds are strong and precise, $alpha$-helix arises, otherwise the $beta$-pleated
sheets form.

The _tertiary structure_ is the compact structure of a protein molecule resulting from the
three-dimensional coiling of the amino acids. They may form due to interactions between amino acids
in close proximity. The interactions may be
- Hydrogen bonds between R groups.
- Disulfide bonds between cysteine molecules. These disulfide bonds are very strong.
- Ionic bonds may form between R groups containing amino acids and carboxyl groups.
- Hydrophobic interactions occur between R groups that are non-polar, and the hydrophobic R groups
  will tend to come together in a watery environment.

_Quaternary structure_ is the three-dimensional arrangement of two or more polypeptides, or of a
polypeptide and a non-protein component such as haem in  a protein molecule.

#point[
